      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so if i'm seeing an increase in neutrophils, i should assume it's a bacterial thing most of the time? and how do the \"left shifts\" fit into that? like what's happening with the immature cells in an acute scenario?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, you are generally correct; elevated neutrophils (neutrophilia) strongly suggests an acute bacterial infection as the primary cause. A \"left shift\" is the crucial detail here, as it means the bone marrow is rapidly releasing immature neutrophils, called \"bands\" or \"metamyelocytes,\" into the circulation. This reflects a massive, urgent demand by the body, indicating a severe and active acute inflammatory or infectious process.",
      "source": "target",
